definition.value: A forest ecosystem which includes communities adapted to 1) hot to warm, dry summers, 2) mild to cold, rainy winters, and 3) the influence of large, usually marine, bodies of water.
A broadleaf forest which is subject to tropical climate conditions.
A broadleaf forest which is subject to subtropical climate conditions.
A broadleaf forest which is subject to temperate climate conditions.
An environmental process either driven by or primarily impacting the parts or emergent properties of an ecosystem.
A mixed forest which is subject to temperate climatic conditions.
A mixed forest which is subject to tropical climatic conditions.
A tropical mixed forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.

A tropical broadleaf forest which 1) s subject to a year-round warm climate 2) may receive several hundred centimeters or rain per year and 3) are subject to long dry seasons which last several months.

value.value: A tropical broadleaf forest which 1) has low variability in annual temperature, 2) high levels of rainfall (>200 centimeter annually), and 3) has tree communities dominated by semi-evergreen and evergreen species.

definition.value: A subtropical broadleaf forest which 1) s subject to a year-round warm climate 2) may receive several hundred centimeters or rain per year and 3) are subject to long dry seasons which last several months.

value.value: A subtropical broadleaf forest which 1) has low variability in annual temperature, 2) high levels of rainfall (>200 centimeter annually), and 3) has tree communities dominated by semi-evergreen and evergreen species.

definition.value: A forest ecosystem which is subject to tropical climate conditions.
This class is primarily to be populated by inference.
A forest ecosystem which is subject to subtropical climate conditions.
This class is primarily to be populated by inference.
A forest ecosystem which is subject to temperate climate conditions.
This class is primarily to be populated by inference.
A grassland ecosystem which is subject to tropical climatic conditions.
A grassland which is subject to subtropical climatic conditions.
A grassland which is subject to mediterranean climatic conditions.
A material entity which has been assembled through the intentional, instinctual, or deliberately programmed efforts of an organism or machine.
An object which is formed as a result of one or more biological processes and is composed primarily of organic material.

value.value: Cell culturing is the aseptic maintainance and growth of collections of cells  outside of an organisms or natural environment in a suitable culture medium.

definition.value: A manufactured product which has been designed to contain a mass of biomaterial.
A biomaterial containment unit which is designed to allow the growth and propagation of the biomaterial it contains.

A biomaterial culturing unit which is designed to promote the growth of selected cell populations (often at the expense of others) within a community by altering the conditions of the environment within its confines.
A biomaterial culturing unit which is designed to promote the growth and propagation of cells in an artificial medium.
Sediment through which hydrothermally modified fluids flow, altering its properties through interaction with their own.
An enrichment culturing unit which contains environmental material bearing ecological assemblages undergoing selection through experimentally imposed conditions.
A plume which is composed primarily of bubbles.

value.value: An ecosystem process during which the species composition of an ecosystem gradually changes as species which are more adapted to the prevailing conditions in the ecosystem replace those which are less adapted.

definition.value: An active enrichment culturing unit which contains environmental material maintained under conditions with no free oxygen.

value.value: An active enrichment culturing unit which contains environmental material maintained under conditions that favour the reduction of sulphate.

An ecological succession process during which 1) organisms in ecological communities possess high adaptation to the conditions in the ecosystem, 2) participant communities largely fill available niches, 3) individual organisms are typically replaced by others of the same species, 4) a near equilibrium is maintained between gross primary production and total respiration and across biogeochemical cycles.

definition.value: An ecosystem which is formed as a result of human activity or impact.
An anthropised ecosystem which is determined by the presence of humans and their constructions.
A biome which is subject to tropical climatic conditions.
A biome which is subject to temperate climatic conditions.
A biome which is subject to subtropical climatic conditions.
A biome which is subject to mediterranean climatic conditions.
A biome which is subject to subpolar climatic conditions.
A biome which is subject to alpine altitudinal conditions.
A biome which is subject to montane altitudinal conditions.
A biome which is subject to subapline altitudinal conditions.
A biome which is subject to arid environmental conditions.
An environment in which living organisms have a low likelihood of being harmed or killed
An environment in which material entities have a low likelihood of being damaged or destroyed.
